  "texts": [
    "In case X is a Euclidean space, these notions correspond to the mass and boundary of classical currents.Thesupport of T ∈ D k (X) is the least closed set F ⊂ X such that T (f, π 1,..., π k) = 0 whenever f = 0 on F.If T is a compactly supported metric k-current on X and Y is a locally compact metric space, F: X → Y is Lipschitz, then we define the pushforward of T under F byF # T (f, π 1,..., π k) = T (σ(f • F), π 1 • F,..., π k • F) for f ∈ Lip c (Y), π i ∈ Lip(Y).where σ is any Lipschitz, compactly supported map on Y with σ = 1 on a neighbourhood of F (spt T) (we need to assume that Y is locally compact to guarantee existence of such σ).",
    "The pushforward of a metric current is again a metric current by definition.",
    "Relationship of classical and metric currents in the Euclidean spaceMetric currents in the Euclidean space can be identified with classical currents using the so-called comparison map.",
    "The definition we use as well as its basic properties are due to Lang [30,Theorem 5.5] though for finite mass metric currents with compact support, this has previously been done by Ambrosio and Kirchheim [2,Theorem 11.1].",
    "For every k ≥ 0, there exists an injective linear mapC k: D k (R n) → D k (R n) such that C k (T)(f dg 1 ∧ • • • ∧ dg k) = T (f, g 1,..., g k), for all f ∈ C ∞ c (R n) and g 1,..., g k ∈ (C ∞ (R n)∩Lip(R n)) k.The map C k is called the comparison map and it preserves all of the important structure of currents, such as the boundary operation and mass."
